data.content:
**What happened:** C# 14 introduces new span conversions. When you call `.Contains()` on an `int[]`, overload resolution now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Since `Span`/`ReadOnlySpan` are ref structs, they **cannot appear in expression trees**, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

**Fix — cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>`:**

```csharp
// Option A: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option B: explicit cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option C: call Enumerable directly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three force the compiler back to the `Enumerable.Contains` overload, which is valid in expression trees. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` instead.
